1
00:00:06,300 --> 00:00:10,700
(Day 1)

2
00:00:29,220 --> 00:00:30,229
Mmm.

3
00:00:30,230 --> 00:00:32,389
- Kasuga Yuma-san, 28 years old.
- This is good.

4
00:00:32,390 --> 00:00:33,700
- Is it good?
- Mmm-hmm.

5
00:00:35,180 --> 00:00:37,800
Hasegawa Itsuki-san, 27 years old.

6
00:00:40,180 --> 00:00:42,763
The two live together in an
apartment in the suburbs of Tokyo.

7
00:00:42,787 --> 00:00:43,640
What is it?

8
00:00:43,970 --> 00:00:46,780
You have some sauce on your mouth.

9
00:00:49,780 --> 00:00:50,780
No, not there.

10
00:00:55,720 --> 00:00:57,550
That's a cute bandage.

11
00:00:57,590 --> 00:00:58,590
Huh?

12
00:01:00,340 --> 00:01:01,440
Oh, it's not that.

13
00:01:03,120 --> 00:01:04,840
It's just the only one we had left at home.

14
00:01:06,600 --> 00:01:08,529
As a same-sex couple,

15
00:01:08,530 --> 00:01:12,500
they registered for the
"Partnership Oath System" last year.

16
00:01:14,300 --> 00:01:15,820
There were two main reasons.

17
00:01:16,380 --> 00:01:18,120
The first was emotional.

18
00:01:19,160 --> 00:01:21,120
We want to be together forever,

19
00:01:22,060 --> 00:01:25,020
so we wanted something tangible
to prove our relationship.

20
00:01:26,300 --> 00:01:28,980
The other reason was a matter of rights.

21
00:01:29,540 --> 00:01:31,520
For a same-sex couple like us,

22
00:01:31,850 --> 00:01:34,719
if one of us were to suddenly
collapse and be taken to the hospital,

23
00:01:34,720 --> 00:01:37,760
the other wouldn't be able to sign
the consent form for emergency surgery.

24
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:40,609
This kind of inequality...

25
00:01:40,610 --> 00:01:43,220
The Partnership Oath System alone
can't completely solve it.

26
00:01:44,300 --> 00:01:46,439
Because the system is just a
local government ordinance,

27
00:01:46,440 --> 00:01:48,400
it doesn't have the same
force as a national law.

28
00:01:49,160 --> 00:01:51,289
Unlike a married man and woman,

29
00:01:51,290 --> 00:01:53,140
we can't receive inheritance rights

30
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:56,460
or get personal income tax deductions.

31
00:01:58,060 --> 00:01:59,989
If we want to have those rights,

32
00:01:59,990 --> 00:02:02,640
we need to achieve
true "marriage equality."

33
00:02:02,720 --> 00:02:07,789
And for marriage equality
to become a reality,

34
00:02:07,790 --> 00:02:11,440
it's necessary for society to
see that same-sex couples exist.

35
00:02:11,880 --> 00:02:13,620
That's also why
we used this system.

36
00:02:14,500 --> 00:02:15,976
We wanted to prove
that if the system exists,

37
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,030
there will be people
who need it and will use it.

38
00:02:20,060 --> 00:02:24,409
After the two were featured
on a news program last year,

39
00:02:24,410 --> 00:02:26,540
they became a hot topic on social media.

40
00:02:28,080 --> 00:02:29,240
(Aired June 30, 2025)
In 2015,

41
00:02:29,420 --> 00:02:33,509
the partnership system was first introduced
in Japan in Shibuya and Setagaya Wards.

42
00:02:33,510 --> 00:02:36,299
It has now expanded to
local governments nationwide,

43
00:02:36,300 --> 00:02:38,890
with nearly 10,000 couples registered.

44
00:02:39,120 --> 00:02:41,819
Now, a decade after its introduction,

45
00:02:41,820 --> 00:02:44,460
how does the public view this system?

46
00:02:44,990 --> 00:02:46,740
How are you feeling right now?

47
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:48,780
Yes, I'm very happy.

48
00:02:48,980 --> 00:02:49,960
Because from now on,

49
00:02:49,961 --> 00:02:52,200
I can confidently say
that we're a couple.

50
00:02:54,300 --> 00:02:55,160
To be honest,

51
00:02:55,161 --> 00:02:58,180
I really did feel like we
weren't "recognized by society."

52
00:02:58,700 --> 00:03:02,080
We're just like any other ordinary couple
you'd see anywhere,

53
00:03:03,020 --> 00:03:05,310
but the people around
us didn't see it that way.

54
00:03:07,540 --> 00:03:09,220
Do you feel the same way?

55
00:03:10,160 --> 00:03:11,160
No.

56
00:03:12,500 --> 00:03:17,260
I've never really cared
about being recognized or not.

57
00:03:19,220 --> 00:03:23,230
But if this guy is happy,

58
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:25,430
then I'm happy too.

59
00:03:28,300 --> 00:03:30,349
At the time, this interaction between them

60
00:03:30,350 --> 00:03:33,810
led to them being called
the "viral couple" online,

61
00:03:33,820 --> 00:03:36,280
drawing widespread attention.

62
00:03:37,580 --> 00:03:38,060
This time,

63
00:03:38,061 --> 00:03:42,350
our program will be closely
following the couple for 100 days.

64
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:48,700
"100 Days with Him and Me"

65
00:03:56,740 --> 00:03:58,820
We've been dating for
about a year and a half.

66
00:03:59,080 --> 00:04:01,440
We started living together
around the same time.

67
00:04:03,980 --> 00:04:05,460
Oh, I'll get it.

68
00:04:05,470 --> 00:04:06,980
- I'll put this here then.
- Mmm.

69
00:04:09,040 --> 00:04:12,040
Back then, I got kicked out
of the place I was living in.

70
00:04:12,100 --> 00:04:13,620
I didn't have any money,

71
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:18,040
And I was forced to quit my job.

72
00:04:18,100 --> 00:04:19,789
Once you come out as gay,

73
00:04:19,790 --> 00:04:22,090
you really run into all
sorts of situations at work.

74
00:04:23,760 --> 00:04:27,760
Itsuki-san used to work as a chef in a bar,

75
00:04:28,580 --> 00:04:31,660
but it seems he had trouble finding
a workplace that was understanding.

76
00:04:32,470 --> 00:04:34,740
He's currently unemployed.

77
00:04:37,380 --> 00:04:40,160
But it's been great living together.

78
00:04:40,940 --> 00:04:43,479
He waits for me to come home
with a delicious meal ready.

79
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:45,880
He's completely won me
over through my stomach.

80
00:04:49,800 --> 00:04:52,099
(Day 2)

81
00:04:52,100 --> 00:04:54,449
After graduating from college, Yuma-san

82
00:04:54,450 --> 00:04:56,690
joined an advertising agency as a planner,

83
00:04:56,700 --> 00:04:58,830
where he's been very successful.

84
00:05:01,400 --> 00:05:03,600
- Morning.
- Morning.

85
00:05:09,560 --> 00:05:11,570
- Morning.
- Morning.

86
00:05:11,810 --> 00:05:13,379
So they're really following you around.

87
00:05:13,380 --> 00:05:14,410
Oh, yeah.

88
00:05:14,920 --> 00:05:16,119
I'm going to be interviewed too, right?

89
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:17,420
Yes, we'd appreciate it.

90
00:05:18,060 --> 00:05:19,699
I'm going to talk so much trash about you.

91
00:05:19,700 --> 00:05:21,439
Go ahead, but they
probably can't air that part.

92
00:05:21,440 --> 00:05:22,440
So cocky.

93
00:05:26,720 --> 00:05:28,479
When he first joined WAVES,

94
00:05:28,480 --> 00:05:29,800
I was the one who trained him.

95
00:05:30,600 --> 00:05:32,636
(Kubota Shinya, Strategic Planner, WAVES Inc.)
He has great taste and his logic is very clear.

96
00:05:32,660 --> 00:05:34,619
He's also great with people,
which is important for a planner.

97
00:05:34,620 --> 00:05:36,459
- It's in Otemachi.
- Otemachi?

98
00:05:36,460 --> 00:05:37,900
This is the first I'm hearing of it.

99
00:05:39,740 --> 00:05:41,860
There's a lot I've learned from him, too.

100
00:05:42,060 --> 00:05:44,239
Like what, for example?

101
00:05:44,240 --> 00:05:46,560
For example... let me see.

102
00:05:47,180 --> 00:05:51,580
Once, I was in charge of an ad proposal
for a real estate agency.

103
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:57,029
In a scenario about helping
someone find a home,

104
00:05:57,030 --> 00:05:59,220
I came up with several ideas.

105
00:05:59,900 --> 00:06:03,830
One of them included a gay male couple.

106
00:06:06,960 --> 00:06:10,070
But Kasuga seemed
hesitant about that proposal.

107
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:12,309
It turns out that this agency

108
00:06:12,310 --> 00:06:17,010
had recently been slammed on social media
for refusing to rent to a same-sex couple.

109
00:06:17,310 --> 00:06:19,480
I didn't know about that at the time.

110
00:06:20,420 --> 00:06:23,249
And I wasn't really aware of

111
00:06:23,250 --> 00:06:27,350
the reality that gay people could be
refused housing by an agency.

112
00:06:28,900 --> 00:06:30,666
If we had gone ahead
with that proposal as it was,

113
00:06:30,690 --> 00:06:34,560
it might have caused a huge backlash
for being so out of touch with reality.

114
00:06:40,060 --> 00:06:43,130
To me, Kasuga Yuma

115
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:48,040
is a planner worthy of respect.

116
00:06:50,210 --> 00:06:52,770
Right now, Yuma-san's team

117
00:06:52,840 --> 00:06:57,680
is working hard to win a proposal
for a major cosmetics company.

118
00:07:00,260 --> 00:07:05,399
Yuma-san's college LGBT
group, "Colorless and Transparent,"

119
00:07:05,400 --> 00:07:07,680
was holding a lecture event,

120
00:07:08,320 --> 00:07:10,519
and our crew went along to cover it.

121
00:07:10,520 --> 00:07:11,420
(Day 21)
By the way,

122
00:07:11,421 --> 00:07:14,600
Kasuga-san, how long has
it been since you were here?

123
00:07:14,630 --> 00:07:18,229
It's probably been five or six years.

124
00:07:18,230 --> 00:07:19,869
- I haven't been back since I graduated.
- I see.

125
00:07:19,870 --> 00:07:22,040
So you haven't been
back once since graduating.

126
00:07:22,070 --> 00:07:25,540
And Hasegawa-san, have you ever
been here with Kasuga-san before?

127
00:07:25,810 --> 00:07:26,810
No.

128
00:07:26,880 --> 00:07:28,179
Oh, so this is your first time?

129
00:07:28,180 --> 00:07:30,300
For Itsuki-kun...
Yeah, this should be his first time.

130
00:07:30,480 --> 00:07:31,510
This used to be a dojo.

131
00:07:32,010 --> 00:07:33,520
Oh, it was a dojo?

132
00:07:33,660 --> 00:07:34,779
If you lived in this building,

133
00:07:34,780 --> 00:07:36,549
you could definitely oversleep
and still make it to class on time.

134
00:07:36,550 --> 00:07:37,550
Totally.

135
00:07:40,400 --> 00:07:45,790
Ever since Yuma-san fell for a male
classmate the summer he was 14,

136
00:07:46,060 --> 00:07:49,576
(Lecture: Learn More About the LGBTQ Community)
he had kept those feelings hidden deep inside.

137
00:07:49,600 --> 00:07:50,699
And this place was where that Yuma-san

138
00:07:50,700 --> 00:07:53,870
first found a place where
he could be himself.

139
00:07:54,100 --> 00:07:57,070
I even met my first boyfriend

140
00:07:57,170 --> 00:07:59,340
through this group.

141
00:07:59,760 --> 00:08:02,960
Then, with the encouragement
of my friends in the group,

142
00:08:03,920 --> 00:08:06,000
on my 20th birthday,

143
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:08,480
I came out to my parents.

144
00:08:08,950 --> 00:08:13,019
(Katagiri Asuna, Representative of Marginal
Women) A woman who can't marry a man is unhappy.

145
00:08:13,020 --> 00:08:16,390
I feel like that kind of
curse still exists today.

146
00:08:18,280 --> 00:08:21,860
When I was little, I
actually hated Girls' Day.

147
00:08:22,500 --> 00:08:24,369
Especially the Emperor and Empress dolls.

148
00:08:24,370 --> 00:08:25,400
They really repulsed me.

149
00:08:26,130 --> 00:08:31,240
I felt like the idea of "this is your
happiness" was being forced on me.

150
00:08:32,140 --> 00:08:36,580
The group "Marginal Women," which specifically
supports female sexual minorities,

151
00:08:37,800 --> 00:08:42,450
is represented by Katagiri Asuna-san.

152
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:47,180
As an openly lesbian activist,

153
00:08:47,260 --> 00:08:49,990
she was also Yuma's
upperclassman in the college group.

154
00:08:52,060 --> 00:08:57,900
Yuma was the only gay guy in the group
I could really talk to.

155
00:08:58,320 --> 00:09:00,739
"The only one" is an exaggeration.

156
00:09:00,740 --> 00:09:02,540
Weren't we debating all the time back then?

157
00:09:04,080 --> 00:09:06,280
That's pretty much all I
remember of you, Katagiri-san.

158
00:09:06,760 --> 00:09:08,579
What was it called again?

159
00:09:08,580 --> 00:09:10,980
Topics like "heteronormativity."

160
00:09:12,610 --> 00:09:14,850
Oh, this guy, in high school,

161
00:09:14,880 --> 00:09:17,990
was apparently so popular with the girls
that it bothered him.

162
00:09:18,020 --> 00:09:19,820
I wasn't that popular.

163
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:22,679
Excuse me, what does
"heteronormativity" mean?

164
00:09:22,680 --> 00:09:23,680
Oh.

165
00:09:24,260 --> 00:09:30,240
In heterosexual relationships, it's usually
the man who approaches the woman, right?

166
00:09:30,670 --> 00:09:33,399
In most cases, both gay men and lesbians,

167
00:09:33,400 --> 00:09:37,610
live as if they're straight
before coming out.

168
00:09:37,640 --> 00:09:40,709
So they end up being pursued
by people they're not interested in.

169
00:09:40,710 --> 00:09:42,799
How should I put it...
that sense of frustration?

170
00:09:42,800 --> 00:09:45,850
Many of the gay male members couldn't
immediately understand that feeling.

171
00:09:46,120 --> 00:09:49,039
Differences like that
aren't always easy to understand.

172
00:09:49,040 --> 00:09:50,090
Right.

173
00:09:51,690 --> 00:09:56,400
Connecting different groups
is what LGBT is all about.

174
00:09:57,300 --> 00:09:59,780
But that point has become blurred now.

175
00:10:01,520 --> 00:10:05,730
That's why I wanted to create a
group that values those differences,

176
00:10:05,770 --> 00:10:08,300
and why I founded "Marginal Women."

177
00:10:09,580 --> 00:10:12,699
When Kasuga-san came out back then,

178
00:10:12,700 --> 00:10:15,180
what were your thoughts?

179
00:10:16,660 --> 00:10:17,860
Well...

180
00:10:20,550 --> 00:10:25,020
But, how to say it... Coming out

181
00:10:27,860 --> 00:10:33,260
is a very heavy, momentous
thing in your own mind.

182
00:10:33,330 --> 00:10:35,730
But for some people,

183
00:10:35,930 --> 00:10:39,470
they can accept it so naturally.

184
00:10:40,140 --> 00:10:41,140
So,

185
00:10:43,100 --> 00:10:44,010
how should I put it...

186
00:10:44,011 --> 00:10:50,179
knowing that I was someone who made
him feel like "maybe I can be accepted,"

187
00:10:50,180 --> 00:10:54,350
that made me really happy at the time.

188
00:10:57,160 --> 00:10:58,160
Yuma.

189
00:10:58,280 --> 00:10:59,280
Look at that.

190
00:11:01,660 --> 00:11:03,840
You guys are pretty popular.

191
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,259
No, we're not.

192
00:11:07,260 --> 00:11:09,360
Here they come.

193
00:11:11,600 --> 00:11:13,500
I told them I don't really
have an autograph.

194
00:11:13,800 --> 00:11:15,240
Just write your name.

195
00:11:17,840 --> 00:11:20,380
Um, I really look up to you both.

196
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:22,016
Ever since you came out, Kasuga-san,

197
00:11:22,040 --> 00:11:24,280
the atmosphere on social
media has really changed a lot.

198
00:11:24,440 --> 00:11:26,040
There's even fan art of you guys online.

199
00:11:27,150 --> 00:11:30,499
Whoa! No way!

200
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:31,500
Wow, so cool.

201
00:11:31,501 --> 00:11:32,590
Thank you.

202
00:11:34,060 --> 00:11:36,539
- Can I ask a question?
- Huh?

203
00:11:36,540 --> 00:11:41,540
Um... what do you like about each other?

204
00:11:41,600 --> 00:11:42,700
What I like about him?

205
00:11:43,870 --> 00:11:45,830
Uh, well...

206
00:11:47,900 --> 00:11:48,900
What is it?

207
00:11:50,360 --> 00:11:51,610
Hmm...

208
00:11:53,740 --> 00:11:55,839
- His face.
- Ah, not surprising.

209
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:57,859
- I totally get it.
- Right?

210
00:11:57,860 --> 00:12:00,150
For me, it's his face too, I guess.

211
00:12:01,080 --> 00:12:02,480
No, wait, maybe his smile?

212
00:12:04,020 --> 00:12:05,759
Though he rarely ever smiles.

213
00:12:05,760 --> 00:12:06,760
Huh?

214
00:12:07,890 --> 00:12:10,240
Itsuki-san, who is said to rarely smile.

215
00:12:10,300 --> 00:12:13,150
We asked people who know
him about their impressions.

216
00:12:14,400 --> 00:12:15,506
(Kitani Toru, owner of the
bar where Itsuki used to work)

217
00:12:15,530 --> 00:12:17,549
Well, if I had to describe
him in one phrase...

218
00:12:17,550 --> 00:12:20,310
I'd say the most fitting would be,
"He's a very straightforward kid."

219
00:12:21,650 --> 00:12:23,869
Right from his interview...

220
00:12:23,870 --> 00:12:25,590
He's really direct about everything.

221
00:12:27,030 --> 00:12:30,550
Like how he'd changed part-time jobs
many times in a short period.

222
00:12:30,610 --> 00:12:34,120
And also the fact that he's gay.

223
00:12:36,070 --> 00:12:38,320
What was the reason
you decided to hire him?

224
00:12:39,490 --> 00:12:42,970
I had him cook something
for me, and it was delicious.

225
00:12:44,490 --> 00:12:45,990
So I hired him.

226
00:12:46,690 --> 00:12:50,049
He can really get along with anyone.

227
00:12:50,050 --> 00:12:53,100
Through his personality and cooking skills,

228
00:12:53,140 --> 00:12:56,170
we started getting more customers.

229
00:12:57,900 --> 00:13:01,200
(Day 42)

230
00:13:01,270 --> 00:13:03,770
So cute.

231
00:13:12,730 --> 00:13:13,730
Mori Naomi.

232
00:13:13,930 --> 00:13:16,950
She's the one who initiated
this documentary project.

233
00:13:17,650 --> 00:13:20,629
She was originally
scheduled to direct it herself,

234
00:13:20,630 --> 00:13:24,899
but she was on maternity leave
during filming and couldn't participate.

235
00:13:24,900 --> 00:13:26,130
But you know...

236
00:13:26,450 --> 00:13:29,610
It's easy for us to stand on the sidelines
and irresponsibly say how cute he is.

237
00:13:30,470 --> 00:13:32,010
Such a fragile little life.

238
00:13:33,740 --> 00:13:36,680
It must be so hard to raise him well.

239
00:13:39,470 --> 00:13:45,120
That's true. It's easy to say "so cute"
when it's not your responsibility.

240
00:13:45,890 --> 00:13:50,090
Or thoughtless things
like "I'm so jealous."

241
00:13:51,090 --> 00:13:53,000
You just mentioned you were jealous.

242
00:13:53,460 --> 00:13:56,430
Kasuga-san, do you want children yourself?

243
00:13:56,930 --> 00:13:58,550
Hmm, children...

244
00:14:00,490 --> 00:14:01,950
Yes, I do.

245
00:14:02,730 --> 00:14:05,829
But for people like us,

246
00:14:05,830 --> 00:14:08,510
it's very difficult.

247
00:14:10,190 --> 00:14:14,010
There are many same-sex
couples raising children abroad.

248
00:14:15,320 --> 00:14:19,320
Yes, but this is Japan, after all.

249
00:14:22,930 --> 00:14:24,330
What about you, Hasegawa-san?

250
00:14:25,760 --> 00:14:27,000
No, me?

251
00:14:28,600 --> 00:14:29,660
Hmm?

252
00:14:30,770 --> 00:14:35,090
I've never really thought about it.

253
00:14:36,930 --> 00:14:41,470
I don't really understand
what "family" is supposed to be.

254
00:14:42,490 --> 00:14:44,139
According to Itsuki-san himself,

255
00:14:44,140 --> 00:14:47,380
he's had a very strained relationship
with his family since he was a child.

256
00:14:48,330 --> 00:14:50,989
As soon as he graduated from junior high,
Itsuki-san came to Tokyo.

257
00:14:50,990 --> 00:14:54,120
He's been living on his
own and working ever since.

258
00:14:54,790 --> 00:14:58,729
So, Yuma-san invited Itsuki-san
to go back to his hometown with him.

259
00:14:58,730 --> 00:15:01,830
(Day 49)

260
00:15:01,890 --> 00:15:05,800
Itsuki-san is finally going
to meet Yuma-san's family.

261
00:15:08,100 --> 00:15:12,100
(Commercial break)

262
00:15:13,650 --> 00:15:15,940
We'll be right back after a short break.

263
00:15:22,130 --> 00:15:24,439
On this day, midway through filming,

264
00:15:24,440 --> 00:15:27,289
Yuma-san, on the anniversary
of his grandfather's death,

265
00:15:27,290 --> 00:15:30,190
returned to his family
home in Shizuoka Prefecture.

266
00:15:35,510 --> 00:15:38,649
This was the first time he
introduced Itsuki-san to his parents.

267
00:15:38,650 --> 00:15:39,670
I'm home.

268
00:15:41,030 --> 00:15:44,069
Welcome back. Come on in.

269
00:15:44,070 --> 00:15:45,869
Welcome, Itsuki-kun.

270
00:15:45,870 --> 00:15:47,310
It's nice to meet you.

271
00:15:47,340 --> 00:15:48,840
It's nice to meet you too.

272
00:15:48,910 --> 00:15:50,010
Please, come in.

273
00:15:50,050 --> 00:15:51,349
Are you filming right now?

274
00:15:51,350 --> 00:15:54,289
- Yes.
- Please, come in.

275
00:15:54,290 --> 00:15:55,570
It's pretty cold here, isn't it?

276
00:15:56,120 --> 00:15:57,550
Yes, it really is.

277
00:16:26,780 --> 00:16:27,780
Here.

278
00:16:30,920 --> 00:16:33,120
Oh, so this is what it looks like.

279
00:16:34,130 --> 00:16:36,630
- A partnership oath certificate.
- I can't see it very well.

280
00:16:37,670 --> 00:16:39,969
See? The names are written side by side.

281
00:16:39,970 --> 00:16:40,970
Oh.

282
00:16:41,490 --> 00:16:44,430
This was the first time we'd
heard of this partnership system.

283
00:16:45,170 --> 00:16:47,060
We were a little surprised at first,

284
00:16:47,440 --> 00:16:51,570
but I guess this is just
one of the ways things are now.

285
00:16:53,270 --> 00:16:56,010
I heard that Kasuga-san once told you,
"I'm sorry, I've been lying."

286
00:16:57,510 --> 00:16:58,510
Ah, yes.

287
00:16:59,650 --> 00:17:01,450
It was on his 20th birthday.

288
00:17:02,350 --> 00:17:04,449
He told us, "I'm sorry, I've been lying."

289
00:17:04,450 --> 00:17:07,850
So I told him, "We're the ones who are sorry
for making you feel like you had to lie."

290
00:17:08,250 --> 00:17:10,230
Whether Yuma is the way he is,

291
00:17:10,260 --> 00:17:12,849
or whether he never said anything about it,

292
00:17:12,850 --> 00:17:16,370
I wanted Yuma to know
that it was never his fault.

293
00:17:17,690 --> 00:17:20,230
He seems like a very honest kid.

294
00:17:20,470 --> 00:17:22,440
He seems very dependable.

295
00:17:23,910 --> 00:17:25,840
And didn't he say he's a good cook?

296
00:17:25,870 --> 00:17:28,030
- He might be even more dependable than Yuma.
- Really?

297
00:17:28,270 --> 00:17:29,350
How should I put this?

298
00:17:29,430 --> 00:17:30,430
Well...

299
00:17:31,190 --> 00:17:34,180
It's like... we're his other parents.

300
00:17:35,070 --> 00:17:37,650
We already think of
Itsuki-kun as another son.

301
00:17:38,030 --> 00:17:40,820
So I hope he can think of
this place as his home too.

302
00:17:42,750 --> 00:17:44,060
What are you making?

303
00:17:45,150 --> 00:17:46,430
Oden.

304
00:17:46,500 --> 00:17:47,700
Oden?

305
00:17:49,210 --> 00:17:50,450
I haven't had that in ages.

306
00:17:51,270 --> 00:17:54,289
Until what age did you use this room?

307
00:17:54,290 --> 00:17:56,869
This room? I went to college in Tokyo
after graduating high school.

308
00:17:56,870 --> 00:17:58,529
So, until I was about 18.

309
00:17:58,530 --> 00:18:01,309
Oh, so it's really been a while, huh?

310
00:18:01,310 --> 00:18:02,410
Yeah.

311
00:18:02,490 --> 00:18:04,279
It's been a long time.

312
00:18:04,280 --> 00:18:06,470
But was this room always this small?

313
00:18:07,220 --> 00:18:09,409
Well, it's your childhood room.

314
00:18:09,410 --> 00:18:11,470
So it's bound to feel different.

315
00:18:11,590 --> 00:18:14,630
I always thought it felt bigger.

316
00:18:16,430 --> 00:18:17,630
A poetry contest?

317
00:18:17,890 --> 00:18:18,460
Huh?

318
00:18:18,461 --> 00:18:19,470
Oh...

319
00:18:19,750 --> 00:18:22,130
It's the kind of thing they
made us write in class.

320
00:18:22,170 --> 00:18:24,070
My teacher submitted it without telling me.

321
00:18:24,370 --> 00:18:25,629
The Minister of Education, Culture,
Sports, Science and Technology Award.

322
00:18:25,630 --> 00:18:26,670
Isn't that amazing?

323
00:18:27,650 --> 00:18:28,706
Itsuki-san, if you don't mind,

324
00:18:28,730 --> 00:18:29,730
could you hold it up to the camera?

325
00:18:29,731 --> 00:18:31,310
No, there's nothing to film.

326
00:18:32,070 --> 00:18:34,890
Back then, the principal even read it
out loud during the morning assembly.

327
00:18:34,910 --> 00:18:36,209
It was so embarrassing.

328
00:18:36,210 --> 00:18:38,010
Huh? How did it go?

329
00:18:38,650 --> 00:18:40,156
I don't know. I've long since forgotten.

330
00:18:40,180 --> 00:18:43,126
So, Kasuga-san, you were actually pretty
good at subjects like Japanese, then?

331
00:18:43,150 --> 00:18:44,150
Yeah.

332
00:18:44,910 --> 00:18:46,039
If I had to say,

333
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:48,290
- I guess I was better at Japanese.
- I see.

334
00:18:48,370 --> 00:18:49,949
Is it this one?

335
00:18:49,950 --> 00:18:50,950
No, no, no, no.

336
00:18:50,970 --> 00:18:52,766
Not that one, not that
one. Seriously, not that one.

337
00:18:52,790 --> 00:18:54,630
You've got the wrong one. Seriously, no.

338
00:18:54,660 --> 00:19:00,740
It contains a poem Yuma-san wrote in class
when he was in the sixth grade.

339
00:19:00,764 --> 00:19:01,906
(Since When)

340
00:19:01,930 --> 00:19:03,570
I asked the night sky,

341
00:19:03,950 --> 00:19:04,969
"Since when has the moon"

342
00:19:04,970 --> 00:19:06,010
"been the moon?"

343
00:19:06,430 --> 00:19:08,190
The night sky answered me,

344
00:19:08,850 --> 00:19:10,570
"Since a long, long time ago."

345
00:19:11,370 --> 00:19:13,070
I asked the summer field,

346
00:19:13,410 --> 00:19:14,719
"Since when have the sunflowers"

347
00:19:14,720 --> 00:19:15,810
"been sunflowers?"

348
00:19:16,490 --> 00:19:18,190
The summer field answered me,

349
00:19:18,750 --> 00:19:20,530
"Since a long, long time ago."

350
00:19:21,170 --> 00:19:22,850
I asked my mom,

351
00:19:23,190 --> 00:19:24,130
"Since when have I"

352
00:19:24,131 --> 00:19:25,230
"been 'me'?"

353
00:19:25,360 --> 00:19:26,560
My mom answered me,

354
00:19:27,070 --> 00:19:29,310
"Surely, surely, it's from now on."

355
00:19:30,800 --> 00:19:35,670
It seems I'm still a long way
from truly becoming myself.

356
00:19:51,230 --> 00:19:53,687
After dinner, his father
suggested setting off fireworks.

357
00:19:53,711 --> 00:19:55,330
- Did you find them?
- I found them.

358
00:19:56,350 --> 00:20:00,830
See? We set off fireworks
all year round at our house.

359
00:20:01,610 --> 00:20:03,829
Today is the anniversary
of my father's death.

360
00:20:03,830 --> 00:20:05,910
Back when he was taking
my mother home after a date,

361
00:20:06,230 --> 00:20:07,419
he wanted to spend a
little more time with her.

362
00:20:07,420 --> 00:20:09,180
So he suggested they
set off some fireworks.

363
00:20:10,050 --> 00:20:11,730
And it was the middle of winter, you know?

364
00:20:12,240 --> 00:20:15,000
He made an excuse, saying they
had leftover fireworks from the summer.

365
00:20:15,930 --> 00:20:17,810
That's when he proposed, right?

366
00:20:19,050 --> 00:20:23,090
So in our family, we can set
off fireworks in any season.

367
00:20:25,410 --> 00:20:29,290
If you were to teach these two the secret to a
long and happy relationship, what would it be?

368
00:20:30,470 --> 00:20:31,949
What do you think?

369
00:20:31,950 --> 00:20:36,689
Let's see... Thinking more about the
other person than yourself, maybe?

370
00:20:36,690 --> 00:20:40,410
Yeah, it's about
consideration and acceptance.

371
00:20:42,430 --> 00:20:44,620
If my parents were still alive,

372
00:20:45,140 --> 00:20:47,940
I wonder what they would've
said if they'd met Itsuki-kun.

373
00:20:50,960 --> 00:20:53,320
I think they would have
accepted him without any fuss.

374
00:20:53,350 --> 00:20:56,080
I really wish they could have met him
while they were still alive.

375
00:20:58,470 --> 00:21:02,220
Hey, should we show Grandpa and Grandma?

376
00:21:02,360 --> 00:21:03,430
Huh?

377
00:21:04,560 --> 00:21:05,590
Show them what?

378
00:21:06,670 --> 00:21:10,400
Like this. Tell them, "We're together now."

379
00:21:12,200 --> 00:21:14,000
See? Just like this.

380
00:21:37,050 --> 00:21:39,399
Perhaps this is how two people

381
00:21:39,400 --> 00:21:42,050
gradually become "a couple."

382
00:21:43,590 --> 00:21:44,929
(Day 62)
Two weeks later, they received a notice.

383
00:21:44,930 --> 00:21:50,470
Yuma-san's proposal was selected in a competitive
bid for a major cosmetics company's ad campaign.

384
00:21:52,130 --> 00:21:56,290
(Komori Megumi, Brand Marketing, Sophia Cosmetics)
The moment I saw it, I felt this design was different.

385
00:21:56,890 --> 00:22:00,920
The message this piece conveys is that
"makeup isn't for others, it's for yourself."

386
00:22:00,950 --> 00:22:03,690
That message, through its vibrant colors,

387
00:22:03,720 --> 00:22:05,750
is expressed so vividly.

388
00:22:06,590 --> 00:22:08,660
If, through this commercial,

389
00:22:09,090 --> 00:22:12,330
we can contribute to building a more
diverse and inclusive society,

390
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:15,000
it would be a great honor
for our company as well.

391
00:22:16,900 --> 00:22:18,600
(Day 85)

392
00:22:18,630 --> 00:22:22,200
On Itsuki-san's birthday,
the two went to Enoshima.

393
00:22:22,290 --> 00:22:24,990
So why did you want to
come to Enoshima last year?

394
00:22:25,210 --> 00:22:27,340
Oh, that was Itsuki-kun's idea.

395
00:22:28,070 --> 00:22:29,980
We were planning a birthday trip,

396
00:22:30,010 --> 00:22:32,050
and he said he wanted to come to Enoshima.

397
00:22:33,090 --> 00:22:34,979
A society full of diversity.

398
00:22:34,980 --> 00:22:36,490
What does that really look like?

399
00:22:38,490 --> 00:22:39,720
Perhaps it's a world

400
00:22:40,060 --> 00:22:43,730
where these two can live as themselves,
walking forward side by side.

401
00:22:48,960 --> 00:22:50,829
That was Plan A.

402
00:22:50,830 --> 00:22:52,030
Hmm...

403
00:22:53,490 --> 00:22:54,629
What do you think?

404
00:22:54,630 --> 00:22:56,270
I think it's well-organized.

405
00:23:03,330 --> 00:23:06,509
Alright, next up is Plan B.

406
00:23:06,510 --> 00:23:07,510
Okay.

407
00:23:08,300 --> 00:23:13,300
(Day 100)

408
00:23:15,460 --> 00:23:16,890
We are truly sorry.

409
00:23:19,230 --> 00:23:22,560
I, Kasuga Yuma, and Hasegawa Itsuki...

410
00:23:22,870 --> 00:23:25,170
when filming for this
documentary began...

411
00:23:25,200 --> 00:23:29,440
were, in fact, no longer a couple.

412
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:33,000
"The Boy and I Who Will Break Up in 100 Days"

413
00:23:45,490 --> 00:23:47,610
(He and I agreed to be filmed for 100 days.)
100 days?

414
00:23:47,660 --> 00:23:49,329
(Next episode)
Their natural selves.

415
00:23:49,330 --> 00:23:51,330
Hmph... "Natural selves," huh?

416
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:55,300
(We pretended to be the "perfect couple.")

417
00:23:55,390 --> 00:23:56,750
Cute bandage.

418
00:23:57,070 --> 00:23:58,430
It's all I had.

